'''George Kamau Muhoho''' (born 1936) is a former Director General of the [[Kenya Airports Authority]] (KAA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/-/1056/555544/-/u3qk07/-/index.html|title=Muhoho leaves KAA post|newspaper=Daily Nation|first=Lucas|last=Barasa|date=1 April 2009|access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref> George Muhoho is a son of [[Chief Muhoho]] and his wife [[Anne Nyokabi Muhoho|Nyokabi]], brother to [[Mama Ngina Kenyatta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200404260369.html|title=Kenya: Why Muhoho Quit As a Priest|newspaper=AllAfrica|date=25 April 2004|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> He was a Catholic priest, and studied until 1968 at the [[Collegio San Pietro]] in [[Rome]] church law. In 1971 he was appointed as the first black African diplomat to the [[Holy See|Vatican]] embassy attache at the EU in [[Brussels]]. In 1972 he was commissioned by [[Pope Paul VI]]. returned to the lay state. He was then responsible for the public relations department of the [[UNEP]] in [[Nairobi]]. In 1976 he married the lawyer Jean Njeri Koinange. [[President Moi]] appointed Muhoho in the Cabinet and appointed him successively with the post of education, tourism and technology minister. In 1991 he left the [[Kenya African National Union|KANU]] and joined as a founding member of the [[Democratic Party (Kenya)|Democratic Party]] of [[Mwai Kibaki]], whose treasurer he is today.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/index.php/business/mag/InsidePage.php?articleID=2000058377&pageNo=3&story_title=|title=Politics: Defections could be costly|first= Wainaina |last=Nudung'u|newspaper=Standard Digital|date=18 May 2012 |access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref> He is also a member of the Council of Elders of the party.
In 2004 he was appointed by Kibaki appointed director of the Kenya Airports Authority (KAA) and has been responsible for the development and also the safety of the Kenyan Airports.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/-/1056/555544/-/u3qk07/-/index.html|title=Muhoho leaves KAA post|first=Lucas|last=Barasa|others= Fredrick Onyango (photographer)|newspaper=Daily Nation|date=1 April 2009|access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref>
