{{for|the American Olympic rower|Joe Dougherty (rower)}} {{infobox person | name = Joe Dougherty | birth_name = Joseph Tapley Dougherty | birth_date = {{Birth date|1898|11|4|}} | birth_place = [[Missouri]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1978|4|19|1898|11|4}} | death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]] | death_cause = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]] | occupation = Actor, voice actor | years_active = 1935–1967 |known_for = Voice of [[Porky Pig]] }} '''Joseph Tapley "Joe" Dougherty''' (November 4, 1898 – April 19, 1978) was an [[United States|American]] [[actor]] and [[voice acting|voice actor]] who provided the original voice of the [[Warner Bros.]] animation character, [[Porky Pig]], starting with the character's debut in ''[[I Haven't Got a Hat]]'' in 1935 until ''[[Porky's Romance]]'' in 1937. After that, [[Mel Blanc]] took over the role and voiced Porky for 52 years. Dougherty spoke with a natural [[Stuttering|stutter]] which became one of the character's trademarks; Dougherty's inability to control his stutter was a factor in the part being recast.
Dougherty was born in [[Missouri]]. Before becoming an actor, Dougherty attended medical school at the [[University of Nebraska]], where he was a member of the [[Phi Gamma Delta]] fraternity. He died in [[Los Angeles, California]].
== Death == Dougherty died on April 19, 1978 from a heart attack. He was 79 years old.
