'''John Davies''' (1795 &ndash; 19 April 1858) was a Welsh Unitarian minister, and schoolmaster. His father was David Davies, minister of [[Llanybri]]. John Davies received some early education at home, his father being a notable Classical and Hebrew scholar.<ref name="Beard1846">{{cite book|author=John Relly Beard|title=Unitarianism Exhibited in Its Actual Condition: Consisting of Essays by Several Unitarian Ministers and Others, Illustrative of the Rise, Progress, and Principles of Christian Anti-trinitarianism in Different Parts of the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=izFiTQ9ADXoC&pg=PA201|year=1846|publisher=Simpkin, Marshall|pages=201–}}</ref> He later attended a local grammar school, and [[Carmarthen]] Academy (1815–19), where his father had taught.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dissacad.english.qmul.ac.uk/sample1.php?detail=achist&histid=63&acadid=206|title=Carmarthen Academy, later Presbyterian College, Carmarthen (1795-1963)|website=Dissenting Academies Online|access-date=24 June 2017}}</ref> Having became a member of the Unitarian Church whilst at college, he began preaching at the local chapel. Later, following the retirement of [[David Davis (Castellhywel)|David Davis]] of Castell Hywel in 1820, he took charge of the churches of Alltyblaca, Bwlchyfadfa, Llwyn-rhyd-Owen, and Pen-rhiw. He also worked as an assistant at the grammar school run by Davis, before starting schools of his own at Gelli-gron, Blaenbydernyn (Pencarreg, [[Carmarthenshire]]), Tyssul Castle, and Tre-fach, and, in 1830, an academy at Adpar, [[Newcastle Emlyn]]. His pupils included the antiquary [[Thomas Stephens (historian)|Thomas Stephens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-STEP-THO-1821.html|title=STEPHENS, THOMAS|author=David Jacob Davies|website=Welsh Biography Online|publisher=National Library of Wales|access-date=24 June 2017}}</ref>

He died in 1858 and was buried in the graveyard of the old chapel at Llwyn-rhyd-Owen.
<ref>{{cite web|title=John Davies|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-JHN-1795.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|last=Williams|first=Griffith John|accessdate= 20 June 2017}}</ref>

