{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox UN resolution |number = 1460 |organ = SC |date = 30 January |year = 2003 |meeting = 4,695 |code = S/RES/1460 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/1460(2003) |for = 15 |abstention = 0 |against = 0 |subject = Children and armed conflict |result = Adopted |image = LimingaSoldier13years.jpg |caption = Child soldier from the [[Finnish Civil War]] }}
'''United Nations Security Council resolution 1460''', adopted unanimously on 30 January 2003, after recalling resolutions [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1261|1261]] (1999), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1265|1265]] (1999), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1296|1296]] (2000), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1306|1306]] (2000), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1308|1308]] (2000), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1314|1314]] (2000), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1325|1325]] (2000) and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1379|1379]] (2001), the Council called for the immediate end to the use of [[military use of children|child soldiers]] and endorsed an "era of application" of international norms and standards for the protection of war-affected children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Security Council calls for immediate halt to use of child soldiers|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2003/sc7649.doc.htm|publisher=United Nations|date=30 January 2003}}</ref>
==Resolution== ===Observations=== The Security Council reiterated its commitment to address the impact of [[war|armed conflict]] upon children and emphasised the responsibility of all parties to comply with the [[United Nations Charter]] and [[international law]], and end [[impunity]] for those responsible for [[genocide]], [[crimes against humanity]], [[war crime]]s and crimes against children.<ref>{{cite book|last=McCormack|first=T.|title=Yearbook of International Humanitarian Law – 2003, Volume 6; Volume 2003|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-90-6704-203-1|author2=McDonald, Avril |page=261}}</ref> It was important that humanitarian personnel had safe and unimpeded access and the [[coming into force]] of the [[Optional Protocol on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict]] was welcomed. The Council further noted that enlisting children under the age of 15 into the national armed forces was classified as a war crime under the [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]].
===Acts=== The resolution supported the call of the Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]] for an "era of application" international standards concerning the protection of children in armed conflict.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cullen|first=Holly|title=The role of international law in the elimination of child labor|year=2007|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-16285-3|page=96}}</ref> Parties to conflict that were using child soldiers were called upon to end such practices while a dialogue would be established with the parties to develop plans to end their recruitment and use.<ref>{{cite journal|last=McIntyre|first=Angela|title=Rights, root causes and recruitment, the youth factor in Africa's armed conflicts|journal=African Security Review|year=2003|volume=12|issue=2|url=http://www.iss.co.za/pubs/ASR/12No2/E4.html}}</ref> There was concern at the list of parties violating their international obligations attached in the annex of the Secretary-General's report and further steps would be taken.<ref>{{cite book|last=Happold|first=Matthew|title=Child soldiers in international law|year=2005|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-6586-6|page=47}}</ref>
Member States were called upon to adopt measures through national legislation to control [[arms trafficking]] in states that did not respect international law (the [[Fourth Geneva Convention]]) relating to the military use of children and protection of civilians during war. The Council was determined to include provisions for the protection of children in the [[mandate (international law)|mandates]] of [[peacekeeping]] operations. There was concern at reports of sexual exploitation of women and children, particularly cases involving humanitarian workers and United Nations peacekeepers.
The Security Council requested the implementation of counselling and HIV/AIDS testing services for United Nations peacekeepers, police and humanitarian personnel. All concerned parties and other states were called upon to ensure that the rights of children were incorporated into peace and [[disarmament]], [[demobilization|demobilisation]] and reintegration processes, and to abide by commitments made to the Special Representative of the Secretary-General for Children and Armed Conflict, [[Olara Otunnu]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Security Council calls for an immediate end to recruitment of child soldiers|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=6026&Cr=children&Cr1=conflict|date=30 January 2003|agency=United Nations News Centre}}</ref>
Finally, the Secretary-General was instructed to submit a report by 31 October 2003 on the implementation of the current resolution, including a specific section on the protection of children in all of his future country-specific reports.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sloth-Nielsen|first=Julia|title=Children's rights in Africa: a legal perspective|year=2008|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd|isbn=978-0-7546-4887-1|page=209}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] * [[List of international instruments relevant to the worst forms of child labour]] * [[List of United Nations Security Council Resolutions 1401 to 1500]] (2002–2003)
